SIMPLE: reticence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reticence
<hw>Ret"i*cence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>reticentia</ets>: cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧ticence</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being reticent, or keeping
silence; the state of holding one's tonque; refraining to speak of that
which is suggested; uncommunicativeness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such fine reserve and noble <qex>reticence</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>A figure by which a person really
speaks of a thing while he makes a show as if he would say nothingon the
subject.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reticency</ent>⟦br⟧
